questions.explanation:
When an event has no `event:` field, its type defaults to `message`, which is what `onmessage` (and `addEventListener("message", …)`) listens for. The moment you add `event: price`, the type becomes `price`, and only a matching listener receives it:

```js
const es = new EventSource("/stream");
es.onmessage = (e) => {};                       // ← never sees `event: price`
es.addEventListener("price", (e) => {           // ← this does
  console.log(JSON.parse(e.data));
});
```

This trips people up constantly: naming your events is great for routing, but you must register listeners by name.
